Date: Wed, 06 May 1998 10:57:11 -0500
From: Tam Garland <TGARLAND@CVM.TAMU.EDU>

I agree with Keith Osborn on most of the things he said, However, I believe
that is grossly understating a point of major impact, 'Oocysts are regularly
recovered during monitoring and yet illness in the community served is not
detected/reported.'
Many members of communities, even in our developed countries, are loath to
seek medical attention unless they are on death's doorstep. Sometimes this
is a financial reason, (such as lack of insurances) sometimes it is fear of
what they may find out. Consequently, that is one huge reason that it may
not be reported. Secondly, it has been my observation that in many
communities, particularly smaller ones, that some physicians are unaware of
the clinical signs and symptoms and seem to believe that if there is no
animal exposure, then there is not a risk, and the resulting clinical
situation is therefore some virus.
I believe that there is more clinical illness from this "emerging" disease
than is being reported/recognized and I think it is a point that needs to
examined more closely. In so doing, it is likely that there would be a
higher rate of infection found. Furthermore, in some cases cities are
reluctant to report that their drinking water may be at fault. After all,
that type of admission causes the public to question its safety and the
responsibility of the city officials, has potentials to decrease tourism, or
other economic impacts, such as companies no longer wishing to locate into
that community. Consequently, crypto is probably more of a problem than is
clearly evident.
--
Tam Garland, DVM, Ph.D
Texas A&M Univ
e-mail: tgarland@cvm.tamu.edu
