[2
Date: Thu, 7 May 1998 9:04:05 +0000
From: David Warhurst <david.warhurst@lshtm.ac.uk>

<Do I detect a little of the reluctance of the veterinary community's
reluctance to acknowledge the importance of animal (domestic or wild) faeces
as a major source of Cryptosporidium oocysts?
Although many waterborne outbreaks have involved treatment process problems,
significant deterioration of source water quality is also a frequent factor.
At the levels used in drinking water treatment, oocysts are to all intents
and purposes insensitive to chlorine disinfection, which is of course why
crypto is of such concern to the drinking water community.>>
The comment of Keith Osborn is very pertinent. In the UK we have recently
had a Crypto. outbreak apparently from a aquifer sourced water supply in the
general North London area. To much surprise.
A few months later Thames Water had an advertising campaign about their
"breakthrough" in supplementing aquifer water sources (probably the same
aquifer) with spare river water. Was I the only one to see the link? Or the
only one to keep quiet?
It would be interesting to see what Thames and the affected water company
think about this.
--
D.C.Warhurst
Reader, Medical Protozoology,
London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine
e-mail: david.warhurst@lshtm.ac.uk
